Rating: 3
One more thing: in France, the batter is actuallly made the day before cooking if at all possible. And I know Proust says Madeleines should be dry and compared to most cakes I agree, but they should not be so dry that they cannot keep for a few days. Generally, these were the kind of cakes taken on long trips because they keep so well.

Rating: 2
I have not made this recipe, but I am currently in cooking school in Paris and we made Madeleines pastry class. In France, the better the bakery, the higher the lump rising out of the top of the Madeleine. All thought the recipe photo does not show the lump side of the Madeleines, its really should be very large and exagerrated. The lump means the cakes have risen properly and should be light and fluffy. So, to the previous reviewer, in order to get a fluffier Madeleine add a little more baking powder, as French recipes I have seen use more (though they also use more butter and more eggs and generally tend to be larger to make the same amount of Madeleines) and really really work the dough to develop elasticity so that the dough will develop a structure as it bakes. This seems to have worked for previous reviewers as one noted that she beat the dough for longer than recommended and the cakes turned out reallly well. When I made them at school, the chef instructors kept telling us to keep beating to really develop the batter. We also really heavily buttered and floured our pans - and I mean heavily, which made a huge difference in the taste and keeps the madeleines moister for longer out of the oven. Ultimately, this may be a good recipe, but I agree with previous reviewers that its not a Madeleine if its not really fluffy and really buttery.

Rating: 3
Even if I would consider making this again, I would definitely change the recipe a little. I guess my disappointment was in the texture or dense-ness of this cookie. Any suggestions? Although I added 1/8 tsp of baking powder, the madeleins still came out a bit denser than the ones I've tasted from Starbucks. I originally used the orange flower/ blossom water (OBW) as suggested by some other reviewers (the french baking and cooking books that I have also calls for OBW), but I think the lemon zest gives it a more refreshing fragrance. Reducing the baking time to 13-14 minutes resulted in a less burned and a more golden color. I used the larger mold pans and this recipe yielded about 15 cookies. The non-stick pans are great, you can forego greasing/buttering the pan. That should reduce a little bit of calories that you can put into having another cookie instead!

